{
  "doc_id": "24033",
  "text": "Several studies demonstrated that melanocortin system is a key point in the regulation of energy balance in fish [CITATION_1] . Thus, in situ hybridization studies demonstrated the presence of POMC neurons in hypothalamus [CITATION_2] but not in the vagal lobe (homolog of the nucleus of the tractus solitarius in mammalian brain). However, more sensitive techniques (quantitative PCR) also reported POMC-A1 expression in the hindbrain (CondeSieira et al., 2010b) . Immunohistochemical techniques further demonstrated the presence of both α-MSH and β-endorphin in the hypothalamus of several fish species, including zebrafish and tilapia [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] thus suggesting that POMC is mainly processed to these peptides. However, ACTH is also present in the preoptic area of carp [CITATION_5] further suggesting an alternative POMC processing in the fish brain.",
